A birthday date night led to trying out Skyline Club and as a couple first timers, we weren’t sure what to expect.  36th floor with a spectacular view of Monument Circle and somehow, that became an afterthought.  The food, without question, stole the show.  If you are reading this, the restaurant is usually available to members only.  I’m not sure how long it’ll be open to the public, so take advantage of this while you can.  View – Best in the city Atmosphere – Elegant, up to date Service – Topnotch, start to finish.  Chef came out, GM checked on us and our waitress was fantastic Drinks – Nice selection, started with champaign and then each had a cocktail – I went with a Manhattan and my wife enjoyed a Peach Cosmo FOOD – Skyline Brussels Sprouts, Pan Seared Sea Scallops, Asian Grilled Lamb Chops, Crushed Potatoes.  The brussels sprouts were quite possibly the best I’ve ever had…and when on any menu, I order.  Cooked to perfection with a chili honey glaze spread over goat cheese.  The crushed potatoes were delicious but as the only basic item ordered, got lost in the shuffle.  We brought most of the potatoes home as leftovers and created a breakfast dish the next day that was phenomenal.  As far as the main courses, we haven’t stopped talking about them.  The Pan Seared Sea Scallops dish was incredible and the thoughtfulness of the plating and pairings with corn puree, risotto, bacon and blackberry reduction made it memorable.  The surprise of the night came with the Asian Grilled Lamb Chops.  No words can do this justice and I thank the waitress for introducing this as a popular selection.  Soy glazed with stir fried veggies and a cilantro mint sauce.  3 lamb chop lollipops, which can’t be an easy item to properly cook, were handled by the chef with perfection.  I’ve ordered this dish from a few high-end restaurants and have never left a review or raved to friends about the experience.  We’ve been fortunate to dine at some great restaurants and we both agree, this is now a favorite.  Do yourself a favor and take in the views of the city, enjoy a cocktail and trust the Chef and his team to handle the rest.

A beautiful view of the city and unlike the Eagles Nest won't make you dizzy from the spinning. The server was great, however the food was just average and in my opinion not worth the price. The food is very good and the brussel sprouts is among the best in Indy. It is made to perfection. The vegetarian entree tastes good too, but the grilled cauliflower is a little underwhelming. The bill includes a service charge even for a couple people. Overall a good spot for a special occasion.

Other than the spectacular view, my dining experience definitely did NOT live up to the hype. Received a phone call ~3pm Saturday afternoon informing me they had "no more slots available for 7, but they would do 8" even though my reservation was confirmed on Friday for 7pm Saturday. Upon arrival at 8pm, the hostess paraded my son and I through the entire dining room, only to laugh and say she had no idea where to seat us since she did not see a table reserved in our name (even though I saw our name written in the book for 8pm). After finding someone to seat us, she simply walked away without apology. Our meals were another letdown... we both ordered the herbed tenderloin cooked Medium Rare (cool red center), but both were served Medium (warm, barely pink center). I requested my meal replaced, cooked as ordered; the plate that returned was less than appetizing. The meat was correct, but the presentation was horrendous. Both my son and I ordered creme brulee... just as disappointing as the rest of the meal, the curdled consistency and chemical taste was unpalatable. When I brought it to our server's attention, she simply removed the offensive dishes and left our bill. I was surprised to see a 20% "Service Fee" already figured into the total, but downright offended when there was a place to add an additional amount. The view and our server, Kyla, are the only decent take-aways from a $120+ meal. Severely disappointed. Will NOT return.

My wife and I went here for the first time for the Valentine's dinner ($69 each). When we arrived the building security were friendly and directed us to the elevators. We got off the elevator and were greeted by a friendly hostess. It was a clear night and we were very happy to be given a table near the window, overlooking the city. What a great view! The food was delicious, the service was prompt, the place was clean. Overall, a very nice place, although the atmosphere reminded me more of a wedding hall than a fine dining establishment. However, not to be a restaurant snob, but for the price, there was one major expectation that fell short. When we've eaten at other places, for example Ocean Club or St. Elmo's, (similar in price), the waiter was very knowledgeable of the items included on the menu as well as being able to recommend potential wine pairings. Wait staff at other places have allowed my wife and I enjoy the creations of the chefs, and learn about foods or preparation methods we hadn't known about previously. At other nice restaurants and clubs, it's not uncommon for the owner or chef to personally visit our table to ask how we are doing.  This adds to the overall experience of dining out (not eating out). Although Skyline Club wait staff were very prompt and the food came on time, one course right after another, the lack of interaction and menu knowledge of the wait staff prior to the meal left me feeling like I was just "eating out" and my perceived value was lower than the level that would allow me to recommend going back or recommend Skyline Club to my friends.
